thoughts.reasoning_problem:
Context: All mammals are animals. All monkeys are mammals. An animal is either a monkey or a bird. All birds fly. All animals breathe. If something can fly, then it has wings. If Rock is neither a fly nor a bird, then Rock neither flies nor breathes.
Question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Rock does not have wings.
Options: A) True B) False C) Uncertain
raw_logic_programs:
Predicates:
Mammal(x) ::: x is a mammal.
Animal(x) ::: x is an animal.
Monkey(x) ::: x is a monkey.
Bird(x) ::: x is a bird.
Fly(x) ::: x can fly.
Breathe(x) ::: x can breathe.
Wings(x) ::: x has wings.
Premises:
∀x (Mammal(x) → Animal(x)) ::: All mammals are animals.
∀x (Monkey(x) → Mammal(x)) ::: All monkeys are mammals.
∀x (Animal(x) → (Monkey(x) ⊕ Bird(x))) ::: An animal is either a monkey or a bird.
∀x (Bird(x) → Fly(x)) ::: All birds fly.
∀x (Animal(x) → Breathe(x)) ::: All animals breathe.
∀x (Fly(x) → Wings(x)) ::: If something can fly, then it has wings.
¬(Fly(rock) ∨ Bird(rock)) → ¬(Fly(rock) ∨ Breathe(rock)) ::: If Rock is neither a fly nor a bird, then Rock neither flies nor breathes.
Conclusion:
¬Wings(rock) ::: Rock does not have wings.
